</mj-text><mj-image src="https://i0.wp.com/newspack-coloradosun.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/09/jeffco-forestry-os-23-scaled.jpg?w=800" href="https://coloradosun.com/2022/09/25/jeffco-forest-thinning-wildfire-mitigation/?utm_source=newsletter&utm_source=The+Colorado+Sun+Newsletters&utm_campaign=SUNRISER_*|DATE:Ymd|*&utm_medium=email" target="_blank"/><mj-text><p style="font-size:12px;font-family:'Libre Franklin',Arial,sans-serif;color:#727273;padding:0 12px;margin:0;"><em>Sandra Carpenter moved into her home bordering the Flying J Ranch in March 2020. Carpenter, an ultrarunner, opposes 2020 forest cuttings by Denver Mountain Parks and has switched her running route to avoid the mulch-filled clearings where more noise travels through the trails. (Olivia Sun, The Colorado Sun via Report for America)</em></span></p>

